rst- and second-generation Asian Americans deal with a range of difficulties, from depression, suicide, and the politics of coming out to broader issues of the model minority stereotype, transnational adoption, parachute children, colorblind discourses in the United States, and the rise of Asia under globalization. Throughout, Eng and Han link psychoanalysis to larger structural and historical phenomena, illuminating how the study of psychic processes of individuals can inform investigations of race, sexuality, and immigration while creating a more sustained conversation about the social lives of Asian Americans and Asians in the diaspora.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAsian American gays. 0aAsian American youth. 0aAsian AmericansxRace identity. 0aAsian diaspora. 0aAsianszUnited States. 0aModel minority stereotypezUnited States. 0aRacexPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aHan, Shinhee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2018z978311069633240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478002680zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478002680423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478002680.jpg  a978-3-11-069633-2  DUK eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles